Week 5 – Day 2
Performance Analysis – E-Commerce System

📌 Scenario
An E-Commerce system must support:

2000 concurrent users
Login response time ≤ 2 seconds
Checkout response time ≤ 3 seconds
Order notification after checkout

Infrastructure Assumptions:
Thread Pool Size: 300
DB Connection Pool Size: 200
Each DB batch completes in 1 second

🔎 Bottleneck Analysis:

1️⃣ Concurrency Bottleneck
When 2000 users hit the system:
Only 300 threads can execute concurrently.
1700 users wait in queue.
Increased waiting time leads to higher response time.
This creates thread pool contention.

2️⃣ DB Connection Pool Saturation
DB pool = 200
Thread pool = 300
Flow:
200 threads access DB.
100 threads block waiting for DB connection.
Blocked threads increase latency and reduce throughput.
If DB CPU rises near 80%, this indicates DB saturation risk.

3️⃣ Network / Query Latency
Even if DB CPU is moderate:
Slow queries
Poor indexing
Network latency
Sequential microservice calls
Can increase overall response time.
This indicates an I/O-bound bottleneck.

🧠 CPU-Bound Scenario Analysis:

If:
Application CPU = 95%
DB CPU = 40%
Then bottleneck is application-layer processing.

Possible causes:

Heavy JSON serialization/deserialization

Inefficient business logic

Excessive thread creation

Garbage collection overhead

Solution direction:

Optimize computation

Reduce object creation

Profile CPU usage

🛠 Improvement Strategies

If DB is bottleneck:

Optimize queries

Add indexing

Introduce caching (e.g., in-memory/Redis)

Review connection pooling

If CPU is bottleneck:

Optimize code

Reduce heavy processing

Scale horizontally

Parallelize independent tasks

If sequential service calls increase latency:

Use asynchronous or parallel service calls

Reduce unnecessary network hops

✅ Pass / Fail Criteria

Performance requirement:

Checkout response time ≤ 3 seconds.

Failure example:

1950 users complete in 1.4 seconds

50 users take 20 seconds

Even though majority succeed,
5% extreme latency violates SLA.

Proper performance acceptance criteria:

95th percentile response time ≤ 3 seconds

Error rate < 1%

CPU utilization < 85% sustained

No timeouts

